By Alaba-Olusola Oke The United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) Office in Akure has lauded the state government for wide coverage of the maternal and child immunisation. Mrs Ada Ezeugwo, the UNICEF Officer in charge of Akure Field Office, gave the commendation on Tuesday in Akure. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the occasion was the inauguration ceremony of the February 2022 Round of Maternal, Newborn and Child Health Week (MNCHW). Ezeugwo described the state as one of the states that had performed well in the immunisation of children and mothers in the country. She added that the state government had improved lives of children and women, saying that the immunisation had reached an impressive level. Ezeugwo urged the government to improve on the success, promising that UNICEF would continue to support it in all areas affecting children and women. In her speech, Mrs Betty Anyanwu-Akeredolu, the wife of the state governor thanked Gov. Oluwarotimi Akeredolu for his efforts towards ensuring child protection, survival and development. Anyanwu-Akeredolu added that the governor provided enabling environment and resources needed for the successful implementation of the August 2021 Round of MNCHW in the state. She lauded the ”Save One Million Lives (SOML) initiative”, State Ministry of Economic Budget and Planning and all partners for their technical and financial supports for children and women. State Commissioner for Health, Dr Banji Ajaka, said that the MNCHW was a week-long event organised to deliver an integrated package of preventive services. Ajaka said the services were known to be highly cost effective for improving maternal and child health survival. Dr Francis Akanbiemu, the Permanent Secretary of the Ondo State Primary Health Care Development Agency, commended the governor’s wife for her efforts in catering for children and women. (NAN)